18:18.160 --> 18:23.320
Martin's first novel was the enthusiastically received, critically acclaimed, Dying of the Light.

18:23.880 --> 18:26.140
The story behind the title of this novel is interesting.

18:27.000 --> 18:28.880
I wrote the book as after the festival,

18:30.920 --> 18:32.660
which was my title for it.

18:34.720 --> 18:36.760
I sold the book to Pocket Books.

18:38.300 --> 18:43.700
At the same time I sold a version to Analog for serialization in Analog Magazine,

18:44.780 --> 18:50.160
and they wanted it cut considerably, so I cut it for them by 30,000 words,

18:51.360 --> 18:54.040
which is a pretty substantial cut.

18:55.480 --> 19:01.280
And when I did that, I said, well, I want this serial version published under a different title,

19:01.560 --> 19:04.840
because I don't want people reading a serial and thinking they've read the book.

19:05.980 --> 19:08.120
Not when there are 30,000 words difference.

19:08.440 --> 19:10.160
The book is a lot better than the serial.

19:12.260 --> 19:16.720
So I told the editor of Analog to call the serial version Mockman,

19:18.180 --> 19:21.640
because my book was going to be called After the Festival, which I've written it under.

19:21.640 --> 19:27.500
He didn't like the title Mockman, but he kind of agreed under protest.

19:29.360 --> 19:35.400
Then my book publisher calls back and says that the higher-up Peter Mayer,

19:35.460 --> 19:38.980
who was running the company at the time, big publishing hotshot,

19:39.280 --> 19:42.540
not a science fiction editor, but the head of the whole Pocket Books empire,

19:42.640 --> 19:49.260
then he didn't like After the Festival as a title, because it wasn't science-fictional enough.

19:51.640 --> 19:56.740
They were willing to make it after the Star Festival, but that gave me goosebumps

19:56.740 --> 19:59.880
and made me want to decapitate someone.

20:00.300 --> 20:01.200
So I said, no, no.

20:01.760 --> 20:03.400
But they threw out After the Festival.

20:03.760 --> 20:05.340
So I had to come up with a new title.

20:05.600 --> 20:10.100
I came up with about 12 of them, most of which were pretty limp, and I sent in a list

20:12.100 --> 20:17.780
of these 12 kind of dreadig which one they would pick, because I didn't like any of them.

20:18.620 --> 20:22.940
And then, like two days after I sent in a list, I thought of Dying in a Light,

20:23.240 --> 20:24.760
and I liked that title a great deal.

20:25.580 --> 20:29.620
I liked it almost as much as After the Festival.

20:29.800 --> 20:30.500
It's real close.

20:30.900 --> 20:33.920
Right now I wouldn't know which title I liked best.

20:34.320 --> 20:36.300
They're both very appropriate for the book.

20:37.660 --> 20:43.880
And the publisher liked Dying in a Light, and I sent it in two days after the list of 12 bad suggestions.

20:43.880 --> 20:46.740
And the publisher said, oh, Dying in a Light, that's fine.

20:47.100 --> 20:47.720
We'll call it that.

20:48.220 --> 20:53.700
At that point, I called up the editor of Analog and said, well, I still want a different title,

20:53.780 --> 20:58.440
but After the Festival is now free because publisher changed it.

20:58.760 --> 21:02.400
So call the serial version after the festival.

21:02.700 --> 21:07.660
So my original title was used on the serial version, and the Dying of the Light title from Thomas

21:07.660 --> 21:10.240
was used on the book, the fuller version.

21:11.320 --> 21:15.600
One of the themes Martin explores in Dying of the Light is that of the misunderstanding

21:15.600 --> 21:18.320
that can develop between people from different cultures.

21:19.540 --> 21:26.840
There's a very significant point of the whole book is the role of names,

21:27.540 --> 21:33.200
which I call it in the book, the importance of names, really the importance of language and linguistics,

21:34.020 --> 21:37.580
to what we are able to think, to what we are able to conceive.

21:37.580 --> 21:43.500
The hero of Dying of the Light, the protagonist, gets in trouble throughout the book

21:43.500 --> 21:46.020
because he insists on making false translations.

21:46.840 --> 21:51.840
He'll see something and he'll say, well, these people are slaves, but they're not slaves.

21:53.620 --> 21:56.720
There's a word for it in the book, an alien word, and it's different.

21:56.940 --> 22:00.960
There are important differences from slavery, but he sees it only in his own terms.

22:00.960 --> 22:06.660
He sees people and he has to define them as friends, let us say.

22:06.880 --> 22:12.740
When the word is tame, it means something very different, similar in some ways, different in other ways.

22:13.300 --> 22:19.620
And to really understand another culture, you have to be able to think in their language, in their terms,

22:19.740 --> 22:27.720
and not make false translations to your own terms that simplify and distort simply by the act of translating.

